\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: Deriving diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this problem, you will be deriving the fact that a diffusion equation
 results from any microscopic picture in which the flow of solute is proportiona
l to the gradient or difference in solute concentration (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Fick's law
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the case of salt diffusing in water within a narrow straw of length
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, which we will approximate as a one-dimensional system.
 Imagine dividing the straw into 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 small pieces of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

, and call the mass of salt in the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-th piece 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{m}\Delta x$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1,\ldots,M$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{m}$
\end_inset

 is a concentration (mass per 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

).
 Suppose that the rate at which mass flows from one piece to the next is
 proportional to the difference in concentrations (
\begin_inset Formula $u_{m}$
\end_inset

), and is inversely proportional to the distance to the mass must travel
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

), so that the 
\emph on
mass per unit time
\emph default
 flowing from 
\begin_inset Formula $m+1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D\frac{u_{m+1}-u_{m}}{\Delta x}
\]

\end_inset

for some constant 
\emph on
diffusion coefficient
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 Derive an equation for the net rate of change 
\begin_inset Formula $du_{m}/dt$
\end_inset

 of the concentration in piece 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Take the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\to0$
\end_inset

 and show that you obtain a diffusion equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $u(m\Delta x)=u_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Don't worry about the boundary conditions; just look at the interior 
\begin_inset Formula $1<m<M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that any salt that reaches the ends of the straw is immediately
 removed (there is a little salt-eating demon sitting at each end of the
 straw).
 What boundary condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{M+1}$
\end_inset

 does that imply in the discrete model? What boundary condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 in the continuum limit?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that we seal the ends of the straw, so that no salt can enter or
 leave through the ends.
 Write down a boundary condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{M+1}$
\end_inset

 that reflects this situation in the discrete model, write the corresponding
 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in the discrete system (
\begin_inset Formula $d\vec{u}/dt=A\vec{u}$
\end_inset

), and write the corresponding boundary condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 in the continuum limit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2: Adjoints in higher dimensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that we have an 
\emph on
anisotropic
\emph default
 wave equation in 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 dimensions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial t^{2}}=\frac{1}{\rho(\vec{x})}\nabla\cdot C(\vec{x})\nabla u$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 is a scalar density (real, 
\begin_inset Formula $>0$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $d\times d$
\end_inset

 matrix: a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stiffness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that depends on direction.
 (e.g.
 think of a stretched drum in 2 dimensions, made of a material that is easier
 to stretch in one direction than in the other).
 Suppose we have Dirichlet boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $u|_{\partial\Omega}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a real-symmetric positive-definite matrix at every 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

, show that we still expect a superposition of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

normal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (orthogonal) oscillating modes (real frequencies) by choosing the correct
 inner product and analyzing the operators, similar to class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 2-component vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 in two dimensions, under the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\vec{u},\vec{v}\rangle=\int_{\Omega}\vec{u}^{*}\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 for some domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 applied to a vector is just the conjugate transpose).
 Give an example of boundary conditions under which the operator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{A}\vec{u}=\nabla^{2}\vec{u}+\nabla(\nabla\cdot\vec{u})=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\nabla^{2}u_{x}+\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\nabla\cdot\vec{u}\\
\nabla^{2}u_{y}+\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\nabla\cdot\vec{u}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

is self-adjoint under this inner product.
 (This operator shows up, for example, as part of the Lam√©--Navier equations
 of elastic solids.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3: Symmetric matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In class, when looking at the balls-and-springs system for varying masses
 and spring constants, we showed that the 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times M$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=-M^{-1}D^{*}KD\Delta x^{2}
\]

\end_inset

is self-adjoint and negative-definite under the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\vec{x},\vec{y}\rangle_{M}=\vec{x}^{*}M\vec{y}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 were positive diagonal matrices (in fact, any positive-definite matrices
 would do), and 
\begin_inset Formula $D\Delta x$
\end_inset

 was our 
\begin_inset Formula $(M+1)\times M$
\end_inset

 difference matrix.
\end_layout

