Construct a 
\begin_inset Formula $5\times5$
\end_inset

 example of such an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in Matlab, using the 
\family typewriter
diff1(5)
\family default
 command from the last pset to construct 
\begin_inset Formula $D\Delta x$
\end_inset

, and pick some 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 with distinct diagonal elements.
 [e.g.
 the command 
\family typewriter
diag([1 2 3 4 5])
\family default
 makes a 
\begin_inset Formula $5\times5$
\end_inset

 diagonal matrix with the numbers 1 to 5 on its diagonal.) Using the [V,S]
 = eig(A) command, as in the last pset, to get the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of eigenvectors and the diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of eigenvalues, verify that the eigenvalues are real and negative and that
 the eigenvectors are orthogonal under the 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 inner product above.
 e.g.
 
\family typewriter
V(:,1)' * M * V(:,2)
\family default
 computes the 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 inner product of the first two eigenvectors, and 
\family typewriter
V'*M*V
\family default
 computes a matrix (
\begin_inset Formula $V^{*}MV$
\end_inset

) of all the inner products of all the eigenvectors.
\end_layout

